## (1)(b) AODV Protocol

> Describe and give the diagram of the IETF AODV (Ad hoc On-Demand Distance Vector Routing) protocol used in MANETs. Discuss a deficiency of this protocol. *(10 marks)*

---

**AODV** is a **reactive** routing protocol for MANETs. It only discovers routes **when needed** (on-demand).

**How it works:**

1. **Route Discovery:** Source broadcasts a **RREQ** (Route Request)
2. **RREQ Propagation:** Each node rebroadcasts until destination is reached
3. **Route Reply:** Destination sends **RREP** back via reverse path
4. **Data Transfer:** Source uses discovered route to send data

::route-discovery

---

**Deficiency of AODV:**

- **High latency for initial route discovery** - must wait for RREQ/RREP before sending data
- **Flooding overhead** - RREQ broadcasts consume bandwidth in dense networks
- **Not suitable for high-mobility** - frequent link breaks cause repeated route discoveries
- **Single path** - only stores one route, no backup if it fails

> AODV is reactive, so there's always a delay before first packet. Proactive protocols like OLSR have routes ready but use more overhead.

